body:
I am not super close to my brother. We grew up in different households (Same mom, different dads, had multiple step parents, etc.) and different lifestyles. He was involved with narcotics and scary folks then racked up some bad debts, so we didn't speak for some time but he seems to be on the straight and narrow since he met his fiance a year ago. I do like to see them, but we are such different people that we have little to talk about. I can tell the feeling is mutual.

&#x200B;

We do Christmas two weeks early. I can't remember why we started but it's a practical lifesaver these days. Since I haven't had an opportunity to give either of them gifts, am very excited for the both of them, and want to put a positive foot forward, I got them a nice gift for Christmas. It's specific, so I can't say exactly what it is, but it wasn't offensively expensive (under $50), included gift receipt, and is something pretty much anyone would like, or at least not be upset to receive. It's like an upscale housewarming type thing, since they just got a place together.

&#x200B;

I gave it to them but noticed no one else got them anything. My brother gave a quick "thanks," which is more than enough for me. But his fiance said in front of everyone that she didn't like one of the things that came with the gift and that it would be a hassle to find a place to put "the whole thing" (for context, isn't big or bulky or dangerous) I felt very sad and a bit embarrassed. I spoke to some cousins who said they didn't get her anything because she did the same thing to them last Christmas.

&#x200B;

Later, my mother pulled me aside and said she felt sad too. I told her that I was just a bit disappointed, but that it was no big deal. I told her I would just avoid getting them presents in the future, and everyone else had already obviously taken the hint. She was upset to hear this and pointed out that fiance's bridal shower was Christmas Eve morning and everyone would be getting her something. I opted not to go because it is rude to show up without a preset to an event like that, but I also didn't want to be in the position of her telling a bunch of others that she hates the gift I got her. My mother is now mad at me, the fiance has posted some thinly veiled "everyone hates me" status on facebook because, apparently, I was not the only one to RSVP no then not send anything, and my brother doesn't seem to want to talk about anything with anyone, saying it would be a "trigger" to be stressed with family stuff, ever, so we need to keep it away from him to support his sobriety. Mom, brother, and his fiance all think I'm TA. AITA? I didn't even think anyone would notice I wasn't there, so I am open to being told I am the ass here.

&#x200B;

TL;DR I got my brother's fiance a gift that she said she didn't like. To avoid a repeat, I didn't get her anything for her bridal shower, which was yesterday, and I didn't show up because it's rude to go to an event like that without gifts. AITA?

